{"id":992,"date":"2023-05-18T21:41:09","date_gmt":"2023-05-18T19:41:09","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/?post_type=glossary&#038;p=992"},"modified":"2023-05-20T21:36:43","modified_gmt":"2023-05-20T19:36:43","slug":"p2p-exchange","status":"publish","type":"glossary","link":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/glossary\/p2p-exchange","title":{"rendered":"P2P-Exchange"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<p>A peer-to-peer (P2P) exchange is a decentralized digital marketplace that allows users to buy and sell cryptocurrencies directly to one another. There is no need for a third-party intermediary. Unlike a traditional exchange, a P2P exchange does not hold user funds or require them to go through an account verification process before engaging in transactions.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Instead, P2P exchanges link buyers and sellers who agree on the terms of the trade, allowing them to make peer-to-peer transactions without the intervention of a third party. The main advantages of using P2P exchanges are that they provide users with greater privacy, anonymity, and more control over the purchasing and selling process.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Furthermore, because P2P exchanges are not custodial in nature, traders have full control over their funds and do not need to worry about security breaches exposing their assets to unauthorized users. A P2P exchange can be used by individuals or organizations in order to buy currencies and commodities rapidly and anonymously.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>All transactions occur directly between two parties, eliminating the extra costs incurred when using a third-party intermediary. Furthermore, P2P exchanges are much more secure than traditional exchanges since they rely on blockchain technology to keep the transactions secure and free from fraud.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>P2P exchanges also provide users with access to markets that may not be available on traditional exchanges, allowing for access to a larger range of investments, regardless of whether the user is an institutional or private investor.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"featured_media":0,"template":"","categories":[24],"tags":[],"letters":[41],"acf":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/glossary\/992"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/glossary"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/glossary"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=992"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=992"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=992"},{"taxonomy":"letters","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/securenest.org\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/letters?post=992"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}